data.reasoningText:
The baseline doesn't even build cleanly because `DateTime` isn't found on the `Order` class. That's because the class uses `DateTime` without a `using System;` directive. Wait, looking at the file more carefully:

```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
class AppDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Order> Orders => Set<Order>();
    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        modelBuilder.Entity<Order>().HasData(
            new Order { Id = 1, CreatedAt = DateTime.UtcNow });
    }
}
class Order { public int Id { get; set; } public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; } }
```

`DateTime` should be available with implicit usings. Let me check if implicit usings is enabled by looking at the project file configuration...

It doesn't have the explicit `ImplicitUsings` setting, but in .NET 6+, implicit usings are enabled by default for `Microsoft.NET.Sdk` projects, so `System` should be automatically included. Yet the compiler is throwing a CS0246 error for `DateTime` on line 11, which is strange since that's a fundamental type that should be available.

Let me add `<ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>` explicitly to the project file to ensure it's properly configured, though this shouldn't be necessary for net8.0. I need to fix the build issues before migrating to .NET 9, so I'll add the `ImplicitUsings` property to the project file and then apply all the necessary changes together: updating the target framework and package versions, fixing the `AppDbContext` to use a constant instead of `DateTime.UtcNow`, and removing the explicit transaction wrapper in `MigrationRunner`.

